1
00:00:06,760 --> 00:00:09,720
(SNOWFLAKES SNARL)

2
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:19,960
(CHILDREN LAUGH)

3
00:00:21,040 --> 00:00:22,040
Walter?

4
00:00:22,160 --> 00:00:25,720
Don't you want to go and play
with the other boys and girls?

5
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:27,440
They're very nice.

6
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:30,720
I don't need anyone else.

7
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:32,560
He never talks to anyone.

8
00:00:33,640 --> 00:00:35,840
He's so alone.

9
00:00:35,960 --> 00:00:37,440
It's not right.

10
00:00:38,880 --> 00:00:40,480
It's not healthy.

11
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:49,040
I don't want to talk to them.
They're silly.

12
00:00:50,120 --> 00:00:51,480
MAN'S VOICE, ECHOING: They're silly.

13
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:02,160
Don't talk to them. They're silly.

14
00:01:06,640 --> 00:01:09,040
Don't need anyone else.

15
00:01:14,440 --> 00:01:16,160
I can help you.

16
00:01:20,040 --> 00:01:21,200
How?

17
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,360
The last of the arrivals
has been sampled.

18
00:01:49,480 --> 00:01:51,520
The great swarm is approaching.

19
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:54,200
As humanity celebrates, so shall it end.

20
00:01:55,320 --> 00:01:57,680
Will the final piece be ready?

21
00:01:57,800 --> 00:02:02,520
It's in hand. I serve you in this,
as in everything else.

22
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:07,040
And do you keep my secrets,
those men who helped us tonight?

23
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:08,560
It won't be a problem.

24
00:02:09,880 --> 00:02:12,280
I promised to feed them.

25
00:02:17,560 --> 00:02:19,160
Oh, beg pardon, Dr Simeon...

26
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:20,600
it's been a long day.

27
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:22,640
I don't see any food here.

28
00:02:22,760 --> 00:02:23,920
I do.

29
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:27,520
(SNARLING, MEN SCREAM)

30
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:28,720
What is this?!

31
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:33,080
I said I'd feed you.

32
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:35,680
I didn't say who to.

33
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:02,800
(WIND WHISTLES)

34
00:03:12,360 --> 00:03:14,360
- Did you make this snowman?
- No.

35
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:15,960
Well, who did?

36
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:19,560
Cos it wasn't there a second ago.
It just appeared, from nowhere.

37
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:37,160
Maybe it's snow that fell before.

38
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:39,680
Maybe it remembers
how to make snowmen.

39
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:41,840
What, snow that can remember?

40
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:44,080
- That's silly.
- What's wrong with silly?

41
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:46,080
Nothing. Still talking to you, ain't I?

42
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:49,800
What's your name?

43
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:52,080
Clara.

44
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:54,240
Nice name...

45
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:55,560
Clara.

46
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:57,520
You should definitely keep it.

47
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:01,280
Goodbye!

48
00:04:02,640 --> 00:04:03,840
Oi!

49
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:05,280
Where are you going?

50
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:07,560
I thought we was just getting
acquainted.

51
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:16,440
Those were the days.

52
00:04:30,280 --> 00:04:31,840
COACHMAN: H'yah!

53
00:04:31,960 --> 00:04:33,320
(HORSE SNORTS AND WHINNIES)

54
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:58,560
WOMAN: How refreshing to see you
taking an interest again. Was she nice?

55
00:04:58,680 --> 00:04:59,840
I just spoke to her.

56
00:04:59,960 --> 00:05:01,920
And made your usual impact, no doubt.

57
00:05:02,040 --> 00:05:04,400
No, no impact at all.

58
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:05,640
Those days are over.

59
00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:07,560
You can't help yourself!

60
00:05:07,680 --> 00:05:08,960
It's the same story every time.

61
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:11,600
And it always begins
with the same two words.

62
00:05:11,720 --> 00:05:13,400
She'll never be able to find me again.

63
00:05:13,520 --> 00:05:16,480
She doesn't even have the name Doctor.

64
00:05:16,600 --> 00:05:18,320
What two words?

65
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:20,360
Doctor?

66
00:05:20,480 --> 00:05:22,440
Doctor who?

67
00:06:14,360 --> 00:06:15,880
Good evening, sir.

68
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,600
Pond's frozen over.

69
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:19,920
Hasn't frozen since the night...

70
00:06:20,040 --> 00:06:24,000
Since the night your children's
governess died, a year ago.

71
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:25,640
Dr Simeon, sir.

72
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,240
He insisted on waiting.

73
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:28,760
She drowned in this very pond,

74
00:06:28,880 --> 00:06:30,800
which then froze.

75
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:34,920
You didn't find her till a month later,
when the ice finally melted.

76
00:06:35,040 --> 00:06:37,200
I recall the incident.
It is the sort of thing one remembers.

77
00:06:37,320 --> 00:06:38,680
Ice remembers too.

78
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:40,560
Who are you? What do you want here?

79
00:06:44,600 --> 00:06:47,000
The pond is yours, Captain Latimer.

80
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:50,080
But what is growing inside it,
when it is ready,

81
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:52,520
is ours. Good evening.

82
00:07:05,640 --> 00:07:07,960
Well, Dr Simeon,
you're out very late tonight.

83
00:07:08,080 --> 00:07:11,080
Almost makes you wonder
what you've been up to.

84
00:07:11,200 --> 00:07:13,520
But then, I have often wondered

85
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:17,640
about the activities of Dr Simeon and
his exceptionally secretive institute.

86
00:07:17,760 --> 00:07:20,520
Well, I am honoured this evening.

87
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:22,400
The veiled detective

88
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:24,120
and her fatuous accomplice.

89
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:25,560
At your service.

90
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:29,360
You realise Dr Doyle
is almost certainly basing

91
00:07:29,480 --> 00:07:31,960
his fantastical tales
on your own exploits?

92
00:07:32,080 --> 00:07:34,480
With a few choice alterations,
of course.

93
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:38,040
I doubt the readers of
The Strand Magazine would accept

94
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:40,440
that the great detective...

95
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:42,440
is in reality...

96
00:07:46,520 --> 00:07:47,440
...a woman,

97
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:50,480
and her suspiciously intimate companion.

98
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:53,760
I resent your implication
of impropriety!

99
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:54,800
We are married.

100
00:07:54,920 --> 00:07:57,840
More than can be said for you, eh, dear?

101
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:03,880
Now, then, this snow is interesting,
don't you think?

102
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,840
The ice crystals seem to have

103
00:08:05,960 --> 00:08:08,440
a low-level telepathic field,

104
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:11,960
almost as if it can detect and respond
to the thoughts and memories

105
00:08:12,080 --> 00:08:13,200
of the people around it.

106
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:15,040
Memory snow.

107
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:16,720
Snow that learns.

108
00:08:16,840 --> 00:08:18,200
How fascinating.

109
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:21,400
I hope it's listening
to the right people.

110
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:24,760
It could be a terrible weapon
in the wrong hands, don't you think?

111
00:08:24,880 --> 00:08:26,880
I think winter is coming,

112
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:30,200
such a winter as this world
has never known.

113
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:32,480
The last winter of humankind.

114
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,480
Do you know why I'm telling you
all this?

115
00:08:35,600 --> 00:08:37,120
I am intrigued.

116
00:08:37,240 --> 00:08:40,000
Because there's not a single thing
you can do to stop it.

117
00:08:41,320 --> 00:08:43,320
Perhaps 7/ can't,
but I know a man who can.

118
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:45,680
I look forward to meeting him.

119
00:08:47,560 --> 00:08:48,880
Do you mean the Doctor?

120
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,480
He won't help us.

121
00:08:50,600 --> 00:08:52,240
He never helps any more. You know that.

122
00:08:52,360 --> 00:08:55,600
Yes, my dear, I do,
so pray for a miracle,

123
00:08:55,720 --> 00:08:57,960
because I think we are going
to need him.

124
00:09:04,480 --> 00:09:08,080
They've taken samples from snowmen
all over London.

125
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:11,000
What do you suppose
they're doing in there?

126
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:13,360
This snow is new.

127
00:09:13,480 --> 00:09:14,880
Possibly alien.

128
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:17,880
When you find something brand new
in the world,

129
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,280
something you've never seen before,

130
00:09:20,400 --> 00:09:21,840
what's the next thing you look for?

131
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:24,600
A grenade?

132
00:09:26,960 --> 00:09:28,320
A profit.

133
00:09:29,480 --> 00:09:31,880
That's Victorian values for you.

134
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:33,320
I suggest a full-frontal assault

135
00:09:33,440 --> 00:09:36,040
with automated laser monkeys,
scalpel mines and acid.

136
00:09:36,160 --> 00:09:37,480
Why?

137
00:09:38,560 --> 00:09:40,400
Couldn't we at least investigate?

138
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:42,200
It's none of our business.

139
00:09:42,320 --> 00:09:45,800
Sir, permission to express my opposition
to your current apathy.

140
00:09:45,920 --> 00:09:47,520
Permission granted.

141
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:49,120
- CLARA: Let me out!
- Sir,

142
00:09:49,240 --> 00:09:51,280
I am opposed to your current apathy.

143
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:53,360
- Thank you, Strax.
- Let me out!

144
00:09:53,480 --> 00:09:58,080
And if ever I'm in the need of advice
from a psychotic potato dwarf,

145
00:09:58,200 --> 00:09:59,960
you'll certainly be the first to know.

146
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:03,680
But if the snow is new and alien,

147
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:06,400
shouldn't we be making
some attempt to destroy it?

148
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:07,440
Be reasonable!

149
00:10:07,560 --> 00:10:08,840
CLARA: Let me out!

150
00:10:09,880 --> 00:10:11,360
It is not our problem.

151
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:15,800
Over a thousand years
of saving the universe, Strax,

152
00:10:15,920 --> 00:10:17,640
you know the one thing I learned?

153
00:10:17,760 --> 00:10:19,240
(CLARA'S SHOUTS CONTINUE)

154
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:21,480
The universe doesn't care.

155
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:23,760
Oi, Doctor! Let me out!

156
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:27,440
Now, we have a problem of our own
to worry about...

157
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:29,240
- Oi!
- Don't worry.

158
00:10:29,360 --> 00:10:31,560
No-one's going to hurt you.

159
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:33,360
- What is that thing?
- Silence, boy!

160
00:10:33,480 --> 00:10:35,960
That's Strax. And as you can see,
he's easily confused.

161
00:10:37,040 --> 00:10:39,240
Silence, girl. Sorry, lad.

162
00:10:39,360 --> 00:10:41,400
Sontaran. Clone warrior race.
Factory produced,

163
00:10:41,520 --> 00:10:45,440
whole legions at a time. Two genders
is a bit further than he can count.

164
00:10:45,560 --> 00:10:49,200
Sir, do not discuss my reproductive
cycle in front of enemy girls!

165
00:10:49,320 --> 00:10:50,560
It's embarrassing.

166
00:10:50,680 --> 00:10:52,640
(WHISPERS) Typical middle child
of six million.

167
00:10:52,760 --> 00:10:54,480
- Who are you?
- It doesn't matter,

168
00:10:54,600 --> 00:10:56,120
because you're about to forget
that you and I ever met.

169
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:59,080
- We'll need the worm.
- Sir.

170
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:01,240
You'll need the what?
The worm? What worm?

171
00:11:01,360 --> 00:11:03,600
Don't worry, it won't hurt you,
but one touch on your bare skin

172
00:11:03,720 --> 00:11:05,800
and you lose the last hour
of your memory.

173
00:11:08,320 --> 00:11:09,240
Where is it?

174
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:10,280
Where's what, sir?

175
00:11:10,400 --> 00:11:12,480
I sent you to get the memory worm.

176
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:13,600
Did you?

177
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:15,640
When? Who's he?

178
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:18,120
What are we doing here?

179
00:11:18,240 --> 00:11:20,480
Look! It's been snowing!

180
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:22,840
You didn't use the gauntlets, did you?

181
00:11:22,960 --> 00:11:25,720
Why would I need the gauntlets?

182
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:29,400
Do you want me to get the memory worm?

183
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:33,000
Well, can you see it?

184
00:11:33,120 --> 00:11:34,720
I think I can hear it.

185
00:11:34,840 --> 00:11:36,520
(SQUEAKING)

186
00:11:36,640 --> 00:11:39,800
Oi! Don't try to run away.
Stay where you are.

187
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:42,760
Why would I run? I know what's going
to happen next, and it's funny.

188
00:11:42,880 --> 00:11:44,320
- What's funny?
- Well, your little pal,

189
00:11:44,440 --> 00:11:46,200
for a start. He's an ugly little fella,
isn't he?

190
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:48,280
Maybe. He gave his life
for a friend of mine once.

191
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:49,640
Then how come he's alive?

192
00:11:49,760 --> 00:11:51,280
Another friend of mine brought him back.

193
00:11:51,400 --> 00:11:52,640
I'm not sure all his brains

194
00:11:52,760 --> 00:11:55,000
- made the return trip!
- Neither am I.

195
00:11:55,120 --> 00:11:57,760
- I can see it.
- Ooh! Can you reach it?

196
00:11:57,880 --> 00:11:59,440
Have you got it?

197
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:02,160
Got what, sir?

198
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:04,880
Because these are the gauntlets,
aren't they?

199
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Sir, emergency!

200
00:12:06,120 --> 00:12:08,160
I think I've been run over by a cab!

201
00:12:10,040 --> 00:12:13,520
There you go. One touch and you lose
about an hour of your memory.

202
00:12:13,640 --> 00:12:15,400
Let it bite you...

203
00:12:15,520 --> 00:12:17,880
and you could lose decades.

204
00:12:21,120 --> 00:12:23,000
And you're still not trying to run.

205
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:27,440
I don't understand how the snowman built
itself. I'll run once you've explained.

206
00:12:27,560 --> 00:12:29,360
- Clara who?
- Doctor who?

207
00:12:29,480 --> 00:12:31,840
- Oh, dangerous question.
- What's wrong with dangerous?

208
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:34,720
The snow emits
a low-level telepathic field.

209
00:12:34,840 --> 00:12:36,320
- The snowman!
- Seems to reflect

210
00:12:36,440 --> 00:12:37,760
people's thoughts and memories.

211
00:12:37,880 --> 00:12:39,400
And because it's unusual,

212
00:12:39,520 --> 00:12:41,400
somehow it carries
a previous shape and...

213
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:44,200
No, Doctor! My snowman!

214
00:12:44,320 --> 00:12:45,680
Ah! Interesting.

215
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:47,040
Well, were you thinking about it?

216
00:12:47,160 --> 00:12:48,200
Yes.

217
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:49,600
Well, stop.

218
00:12:50,480 --> 00:12:52,400
Clara, stop thinking about the snowmen!

219
00:12:53,280 --> 00:12:54,480
Get down!

220
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:57,400
Clara, listen to me.

221
00:12:57,520 --> 00:12:59,840
- The snow's feeding off your thoughts.
- I don't understand.

222
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:02,040
You're caught in their telepathic field.
They're mirroring you.

223
00:13:02,160 --> 00:13:04,480
The more you think about the snowmen,
the more they appear.

224
00:13:04,600 --> 00:13:06,720
Imagine them melted. Picture it.
Picture them melted!

225
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:13,640
Well, very good.

226
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:16,360
Very, very good! Ha!

227
00:13:16,480 --> 00:13:18,480
Is that going to happen again?

228
00:13:18,600 --> 00:13:20,960
Well, if it does,
you know what to do about it.

229
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:23,520
Unless I forget.

230
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:28,680
Don't come looking for me.
Forget about me. You understand?

231
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:30,000
What about the snow?

232
00:13:30,120 --> 00:13:31,840
Shouldn't we be warning people?

233
00:13:31,960 --> 00:13:32,880
Not my problem.

234
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:34,560
Merry Christmas!

235
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:36,360
Take her back where we found her.

236
00:13:36,480 --> 00:13:37,560
Sir.

237
00:13:57,040 --> 00:14:01,480
(HE WHISTLES "Silent Night")

238
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:33,760
(DOOR SLAMS SHUT)

239
00:15:10,840 --> 00:15:12,800
Come on...

240
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:36,640
Hello.

241
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:41,440
Invisible.

242
00:15:41,560 --> 00:15:43,080
(CLATTERING AND FOOTSTEPS)

243
00:15:49,920 --> 00:15:51,720
An invisible staircase.

244
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:15,400
(WIND WHISTLES)

245
00:16:46,360 --> 00:16:47,880
(SHE GASPS)

246
00:16:53,480 --> 00:16:54,680
(METALLIC SPRINGING)

247
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:07,800
(ELECTRONIC BURBLING)

248
00:17:13,200 --> 00:17:14,880
(CHIRRUPING BUZZ)

249
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:22,600
Hello?

250
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:32,360
Hello?

251
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:40,240
Hello?

252
00:18:03,280 --> 00:18:06,120
Tonight the thaw,

253
00:18:06,240 --> 00:18:08,880
tomorrow the snow will
fall again yet stronger.

254
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,240
The drowned woman and the dreaming child
will give us form

255
00:18:12,360 --> 00:18:13,880
at last.

256
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,600
Tomorrow the snow will fall
and so shall mankind.

257
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:20,440
She is coming.

258
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:24,520
(DISTANT CHURCH BELLS CHIME)

259
00:18:43,160 --> 00:18:45,720
Look at that.
Must have thawed in the night.

260
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,080
I'm begging you, Clara.

261
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:49,200
I'm on my knees.

262
00:18:49,320 --> 00:18:50,600
Elsie's back this afternoon.

263
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:52,640
And I was only helping out.

264
00:18:52,760 --> 00:18:54,680
- I've got my own work to get back to.
- What work?

265
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:56,880
Why won't you ever tell us?

266
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,360
You'd never believe me. (BLOWS KISS)

267
00:19:13,120 --> 00:19:14,640
Whoa!

268
00:19:19,800 --> 00:19:21,160
Alice,

269
00:19:21,280 --> 00:19:22,480
how smart you look today.

270
00:19:22,600 --> 00:19:24,720
The governess should enter
by the back door,

271
00:19:24,840 --> 00:19:26,880
unless accompanied by the children.

272
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:27,960
Hm!

273
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:30,600
And how are the children?
Excited about tomorrow?

274
00:19:30,720 --> 00:19:32,640
Francesca same as ever.

275
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:34,800
Digby said he missed you every day.

276
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:36,680
Captain Latimer wants to see you.

277
00:19:36,800 --> 00:19:38,080
Of course.

278
00:19:42,600 --> 00:19:43,520
Every day?

279
00:19:43,640 --> 00:19:44,760
Twice on Saturdays.

280
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:47,200
That's better.

281
00:19:49,400 --> 00:19:50,960
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

282
00:19:54,800 --> 00:19:56,240
Captain Latimer.

283
00:19:56,360 --> 00:19:57,840
Ah!

284
00:19:57,960 --> 00:19:59,240
Miss Montague, you're back.

285
00:19:59,360 --> 00:20:00,360
In time for Christmas.

286
00:20:00,480 --> 00:20:02,760
Apologies for my brief absence.

287
00:20:02,880 --> 00:20:04,720
Family illness is so unpredictable.

288
00:20:04,840 --> 00:20:06,360
You wanted to see me?

289
00:20:06,480 --> 00:20:08,800
Francesca has been having nightmares.

290
00:20:08,920 --> 00:20:11,320
- Young girls often do.
- Every night this week, she says.

291
00:20:11,440 --> 00:20:12,880
Won't tell me about them.

292
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:15,320
Perhaps if you asked her
in the right way...

293
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:16,720
There's no-one she'd rather tell.

294
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:19,280
Children are...not...

295
00:20:19,400 --> 00:20:20,640
really my area of expertise.

296
00:20:20,760 --> 00:20:23,600
They are, however, your children.

297
00:20:23,720 --> 00:20:25,440
You have, if I may say,

298
00:20:25,560 --> 00:20:27,960
a remarkable amount of wisdom
in these matters for one so...

299
00:20:29,680 --> 00:20:31,320
...very pretty, Miss Montague.

300
00:20:32,560 --> 00:20:34,160
Young...

301
00:20:34,280 --> 00:20:35,880
I mean.

302
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:37,920
I'll see to the children now.

303
00:20:39,120 --> 00:20:40,720
(CHILDREN LAUGH)

304
00:20:46,160 --> 00:20:47,120
Miss Montague!

305
00:20:47,240 --> 00:20:48,680
Miss Montague, you're back!

306
00:20:48,800 --> 00:20:50,080
Ah, ah, ah!

307
00:20:50,200 --> 00:20:52,720
- Good morning, Miss Montague.
- Good morning, Miss Montague.

308
00:20:52,840 --> 00:20:55,240
Good morning, Francesca.
Good morning, Digby.

309
00:20:55,360 --> 00:20:57,360
Christmas Eve is the most thrilling day,
don't you think?

310
00:20:57,480 --> 00:21:00,080
Now, what have you two been up to
while I've been away?

311
00:21:00,200 --> 00:21:01,640
I did seven drawings.

312
00:21:01,760 --> 00:21:03,640
And we saw a dead cow.

313
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:06,920
Well, how exciting!

314
00:21:07,040 --> 00:21:08,760
Do your secret voice.

315
00:21:12,600 --> 00:21:13,600
'Ello, mates!

316
00:21:15,880 --> 00:21:19,240
They're not exactly nightmares.
Just dreams.

317
00:21:19,360 --> 00:21:21,640
About our old governess,
the one who died.

318
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:24,000
She's haunting Frannie
from beyond the grave.

319
00:21:25,720 --> 00:21:27,880
Haven't you spoken
to your father about this?

320
00:21:29,160 --> 00:21:31,720
You can't talk about things like that
to Daddy.

321
00:21:31,840 --> 00:21:33,360
You could try.

322
00:21:33,480 --> 00:21:35,240
Do you want to see where she died?

323
00:21:36,880 --> 00:21:39,480
She fell in there.

324
00:21:39,600 --> 00:21:41,840
And then it froze.

325
00:21:41,960 --> 00:21:44,440
She was in the ice for days and days.

326
00:21:47,160 --> 00:21:48,880
I hated her.

327
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:51,120
She was cross all the time.

328
00:21:51,240 --> 00:21:55,880
In Frannie's dream, she's still
down there, waiting to come back.

329
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,560
Everything else has thawed,
but this pond...

330
00:22:00,080 --> 00:22:01,760
...Is still frozen.

331
00:22:04,800 --> 00:22:06,600
THE DOCTOR: The snow's feeding off
your thoughts.

332
00:22:06,720 --> 00:22:09,000
The more you think about the snowmen,
the more they appear.

333
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:11,160
Frannie,

334
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:12,360
this is important.

335
00:22:12,480 --> 00:22:14,960
You dream about her. What do you dream?

336
00:22:15,080 --> 00:22:16,880
She's cross with me.

337
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:18,600
She says I've been bad

338
00:22:18,720 --> 00:22:20,000
and she's going to come out of the pond

339
00:22:20,120 --> 00:22:21,680
- and punish me.
- When?

340
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:23,680
She said she'd come back for Christmas.

341
00:22:23,800 --> 00:22:25,320
Tonight.

342
00:22:25,440 --> 00:22:28,160
I think Frannie's gone mad. Don't you?

343
00:22:28,280 --> 00:22:29,600
I think she needs a doctor.

344
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:44,360
Doctor!

345
00:22:45,440 --> 00:22:46,680
Doctor!

346
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:48,440
What's she looking at?!

347
00:22:50,760 --> 00:22:52,480
She's asking for a doctor.

348
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:55,480
Doctor!

349
00:22:57,440 --> 00:22:59,560
Now, then, that's enough noise!

350
00:22:59,680 --> 00:23:01,520
We don't want to attract attention,
do we?

351
00:23:01,640 --> 00:23:04,160
I'm looking for the Doctor.
Do you know about him? The Doctor?

352
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:06,240
Doctor who?

353
00:23:11,080 --> 00:23:14,760
Do not attempt to escape
or you will be obliterated.

354
00:23:14,880 --> 00:23:16,240
May I take your coat?

355
00:23:27,760 --> 00:23:29,240
Sit.

356
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:35,920
There are two refreshments

357
00:23:36,040 --> 00:23:38,280
in your world the colour of red wine.

358
00:23:38,400 --> 00:23:40,720
This...is not

359
00:23:40,840 --> 00:23:42,080
red wine.

360
00:23:42,200 --> 00:23:43,960
Madame Vastra will ask you questions.

361
00:23:44,080 --> 00:23:47,160
You will confine yourself
to single-word responses.

362
00:23:47,280 --> 00:23:49,200
One word only.

363
00:23:49,320 --> 00:23:51,520
Do you understand?

364
00:23:51,640 --> 00:23:52,560
Why?

365
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:55,480
Truth is singular. Lies are words,

366
00:23:55,600 --> 00:23:57,280
words, words.

367
00:23:58,560 --> 00:24:00,560
- You met the Doctor, didn't you?
- Yes.

368
00:24:00,680 --> 00:24:03,320
And now you've come
looking for him again. Why?

369
00:24:05,320 --> 00:24:06,640
Take your time.

370
00:24:07,920 --> 00:24:10,040
One word only.

371
00:24:10,160 --> 00:24:11,720
Curiosity.

372
00:24:11,840 --> 00:24:12,840
- About?
- Snow.

373
00:24:12,960 --> 00:24:14,800
- And about him?
- Yes.

374
00:24:14,920 --> 00:24:15,920
What do you want from him?

375
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:17,360
- Help.
- Why?

376
00:24:17,480 --> 00:24:18,400
Danger.

377
00:24:18,520 --> 00:24:20,280
Why would he help you?

378
00:24:22,600 --> 00:24:23,760
Kindness.

379
00:24:24,920 --> 00:24:26,920
The Doctor is not kind.

380
00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:28,520
No?

381
00:24:28,640 --> 00:24:30,760
No. The Doctor doesn't help people.

382
00:24:30,880 --> 00:24:32,880
Not anyone, not ever.

383
00:24:33,960 --> 00:24:36,520
He stands above this world

384
00:24:36,640 --> 00:24:39,640
and doesn't interfere
in the affairs of its inhabitants.

385
00:24:39,760 --> 00:24:42,920
He is not your salvation
nor your protector.

386
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:46,640
Do you understand
what I am saying to you?

387
00:24:48,880 --> 00:24:49,880
Words.

388
00:24:52,960 --> 00:24:56,320
He was different once...

389
00:24:56,440 --> 00:24:57,680
a long time ago.

390
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:00,840
Kind, yes.

391
00:25:02,080 --> 00:25:03,680
A hero, even,

392
00:25:03,800 --> 00:25:06,160
a saver of worlds.

393
00:25:07,840 --> 00:25:11,040
But he suffered losses which hurt him.

394
00:25:12,320 --> 00:25:16,160
Now he prefers isolation
to the possibility of pain's return.

395
00:25:19,040 --> 00:25:21,600
Kindly choose a word to indicate

396
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:23,360
your understanding of this.

397
00:25:27,520 --> 00:25:28,520
Man.

398
00:25:34,560 --> 00:25:36,480
We are the Doctor's friends.

399
00:25:36,600 --> 00:25:41,360
We assist him in his isolation,
but that does not mean we approve of it.

400
00:25:41,480 --> 00:25:42,880
So...

401
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:46,400
...a test for you.

402
00:25:48,960 --> 00:25:50,960
Give me a message for the Doctor.

403
00:25:51,080 --> 00:25:52,360
Tell him all about the snow

404
00:25:52,480 --> 00:25:54,960
and what fresh danger
you believe it presents,

405
00:25:55,080 --> 00:25:56,240
and above all...

406
00:25:57,320 --> 00:26:00,120
...explain why he should help you.

407
00:26:02,240 --> 00:26:04,440
But do it in one word.

408
00:26:08,720 --> 00:26:11,120
You are thinking it's impossible
such a word exists

409
00:26:11,240 --> 00:26:13,000
or that you could even find it.

410
00:26:14,560 --> 00:26:17,040
Let's see if the gods are with you.

411
00:26:18,360 --> 00:26:20,440
(PHONE RINGS)

412
00:26:25,680 --> 00:26:26,680
Yes?

413
00:26:26,800 --> 00:26:28,480
What? I'm trying to read.

414
00:26:28,600 --> 00:26:30,920
Miss Clara and her concerns
about the snow.

415
00:26:31,040 --> 00:26:32,760
I gave her the one-word test.

416
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:35,240
It's always pointless. What did she say?

417
00:26:36,560 --> 00:26:38,120
Well?

418
00:26:38,240 --> 00:26:39,320
Well?!

419
00:26:40,360 --> 00:26:41,600
Pond.

420
00:26:48,080 --> 00:26:51,080
Strax has already suggested
where to start investigating.

421
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:58,400
Danger.

422
00:26:58,520 --> 00:27:00,320
- Danger!
- What's wrong?

423
00:27:00,440 --> 00:27:04,320
There is danger here, an intelligence,

424
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:07,000
an intelligence beyond anything else

425
00:27:07,120 --> 00:27:08,480
in this time and place.

426
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:13,360
Dr Simeon, sir, there's someone
demanding to see you.

427
00:27:13,480 --> 00:27:15,160
No callers, not in here, not ever.

428
00:27:15,280 --> 00:27:17,080
- Did he leave his name?
- Sir...

429
00:27:17,200 --> 00:27:19,160
it's Sherlock Holmes!

430
00:27:22,400 --> 00:27:24,200
Oh, yeah! Nice office.

431
00:27:24,320 --> 00:27:26,240
Big globey thing. Now...

432
00:27:26,360 --> 00:27:28,440
shut up, don't tell me.
I see from your collar stud

433
00:27:28,560 --> 00:27:30,400
you have an apple tree
and a wife with a limp. Am I right?

434
00:27:30,520 --> 00:27:32,200
- No.
- But you have a wife?

435
00:27:32,320 --> 00:27:33,760
- No.
- Bit of a tree? Bit of a wife?

436
00:27:33,880 --> 00:27:35,160
Some apples?

437
00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:36,640
Come on, work with me here.

438
00:27:36,760 --> 00:27:39,120
1 enjoy The Strand Magazine
as much as the next man,

439
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:41,840
but I'm perfectly aware that Sherlock
Holmes is a fictional character.

440
00:27:41,960 --> 00:27:44,000
- Get out!
- Do you have a goldfish named Colin?

441
00:27:44,120 --> 00:27:45,040
No.

442
00:27:45,160 --> 00:27:47,120
Thought not.

443
00:27:47,240 --> 00:27:48,320
Now...

444
00:27:48,440 --> 00:27:50,480
Ooh! I see this is
one of your business cards.

445
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:51,800
It says so on the front.

446
00:27:51,920 --> 00:27:53,640
Who are you,
and what are you doing here?

447
00:27:55,840 --> 00:27:56,760
This.

448
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:58,640
Wakey, wakey!

449
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:03,160
That is highly valuable equipment.

450
00:28:03,280 --> 00:28:05,040
You must step away now.

451
00:28:05,160 --> 00:28:07,120
We are the Intelligence.

452
00:28:07,240 --> 00:28:08,240
Oh!

453
00:28:08,360 --> 00:28:11,600
Talking snow. I love new things.

454
00:28:11,720 --> 00:28:13,480
You are not of this world.

455
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:15,320
Takes one to snow one!

456
00:28:20,120 --> 00:28:21,800
Right, let's see.

457
00:28:21,920 --> 00:28:24,840
Multinucleate crystalline organism
with the ability

458
00:28:24,960 --> 00:28:26,720
to mimic and mirror what it finds.

459
00:28:26,840 --> 00:28:28,560
Looks like snow. Isn't snow.

460
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:30,160
You must leave here now!

461
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:32,400
Shut up, I'm making deductions.
It's very exciting.

462
00:28:32,520 --> 00:28:35,320
Now, what are you, eh?

463
00:28:35,440 --> 00:28:37,560
A flock of space crystals?

464
00:28:37,680 --> 00:28:39,120
A swarm?

465
00:28:39,240 --> 00:28:40,840
- (RINGS BELL)
- The snowmen are foot soldiers,

466
00:28:40,960 --> 00:28:41,880
mindless predators.

467
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,800
But you, you're the clever one.
You're Moriarty.

468
00:28:44,920 --> 00:28:46,440
So you turn up on a planet,

469
00:28:46,560 --> 00:28:48,880
you generate a telepathic field
to learn what you can.

470
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:50,720
- (DOOR LOCKS)
- And when you've learnt enough...

471
00:28:51,760 --> 00:28:54,160
...what do you do?

472
00:28:54,280 --> 00:28:55,880
You can't conquer the world
using snowmen.

473
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:57,760
Snowmen are rubbish in July.

474
00:28:57,880 --> 00:28:59,560
You'll have to be better than that.

475
00:28:59,680 --> 00:29:01,320
You'll have to evolve.

476
00:29:01,440 --> 00:29:03,400
Sir? It appears to be stuck!

477
00:29:03,520 --> 00:29:05,240
What have you done?
Have you locked the doors?

478
00:29:05,360 --> 00:29:07,120
You need to translate yourself

479
00:29:07,240 --> 00:29:08,840
into something more...

480
00:29:08,960 --> 00:29:10,040
well...

481
00:29:10,160 --> 00:29:11,080
human.

482
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:12,440
- Kick it down!
- To do that,

483
00:29:12,560 --> 00:29:15,040
you need a perfect duplicate
of human DNA in ice form.

484
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:16,760
Where do you find...

485
00:29:16,880 --> 00:29:18,320
- that?
- Sir!

486
00:29:18,440 --> 00:29:19,600
Get in here! Quickly!

487
00:29:19,720 --> 00:29:21,120
I've got a master key somewhere, sir.

488
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:23,800
Now, let's see. Most opened file.

489
00:29:24,480 --> 00:29:26,040
Most viewed page.
You know, you really should

490
00:29:26,160 --> 00:29:27,960
delete your history.

491
00:29:28,080 --> 00:29:30,560
"Governess frozen in pond.”

492
00:29:30,680 --> 00:29:31,960
Gotcha!

493
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:33,080
Got it, sir!

494
00:29:34,160 --> 00:29:35,480
Get in here!

495
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:36,880
Take him downstairs.

496
00:29:42,840 --> 00:29:45,320
Body frozen in a pond...

497
00:29:45,440 --> 00:29:50,640
where the snow gets a good, long look
at a human being, like a full body scan.

498
00:29:50,760 --> 00:29:52,200
Everything they need to evolve.

499
00:29:52,320 --> 00:29:53,720
A pond.

500
00:29:53,840 --> 00:29:55,920
Good point, Clara.

501
00:29:58,640 --> 00:30:00,480
What are you doing here?

502
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:02,720
Madame Vastra wondered
if you were needing any grenades.

503
00:30:02,840 --> 00:30:03,840
Grenades?!

504
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:06,560
She might have said "help".

505
00:30:06,680 --> 00:30:07,960
Help for what?

506
00:30:08,080 --> 00:30:10,080
Well...your investigation.

507
00:30:10,200 --> 00:30:12,640
Investigation?
Who says I'm investigating?

508
00:30:12,760 --> 00:30:14,360
Do you think I'm going
to start investigating

509
00:30:14,480 --> 00:30:17,080
just because some bird smiles at me?

510
00:30:17,200 --> 00:30:18,600
Who do you think I am?

511
00:30:19,680 --> 00:30:21,160
Sherlock Holmes.

512
00:30:25,440 --> 00:30:28,600
Don't be clever, Strax.
It doesn't suit you.

513
00:30:28,720 --> 00:30:29,760
Sorry, sir.

514
00:30:29,880 --> 00:30:32,400
I'm the clever one,
you're the potato one.

515
00:30:32,520 --> 00:30:33,440
Yes, sir.

516
00:30:33,560 --> 00:30:34,760
Now go away.

517
00:30:34,880 --> 00:30:36,240
Yes...

518
00:30:36,360 --> 00:30:38,000
Mr Holmes.

519
00:30:38,120 --> 00:30:39,080
- Oi!
- (CHUCKLES)

520
00:30:39,200 --> 00:30:40,520
Shut up, you're not clever

521
00:30:40,640 --> 00:30:41,760
or funny

522
00:30:41,880 --> 00:30:43,640
and you've got tiny little legs!

523
00:31:04,080 --> 00:31:06,600
OK, just tell her you're leaving,
you're not going up.

524
00:31:06,720 --> 00:31:08,400
(WHISPERS) I'm leaving,
I'm not going up.

525
00:31:11,200 --> 00:31:13,040
What was that all about? Five minutes?

526
00:31:13,160 --> 00:31:14,880
Where did that come from? You...!

527
00:31:23,360 --> 00:31:27,080
It's the human male from the institute.
What's he doing here?

528
00:31:28,880 --> 00:31:32,120
I suggest we melt his brain
using projectile acid fish

529
00:31:32,240 --> 00:31:34,080
and then interrogate him.

530
00:31:36,400 --> 00:31:37,720
Other way round.

531
00:31:38,800 --> 00:31:41,440
Am I going to have
the nightmare tonight?

532
00:31:41,560 --> 00:31:43,480
Definitely not.

533
00:31:43,600 --> 00:31:45,120
- How do you know?
- Because...

534
00:31:45,240 --> 00:31:47,240
someone's coming to help.

535
00:31:47,360 --> 00:31:48,480
Who?

536
00:31:49,520 --> 00:31:51,560
You wouldn't believe me if I told you.

537
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:54,880
Is it one of your stories?
Your definitely true ones?

538
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:56,840
Huh! ALI my stories are true.

539
00:31:56,960 --> 00:31:59,000
Like how you were born
behind the clock face of Big Ben?

540
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:01,000
Accounting for my acute sense of time.

541
00:32:01,120 --> 00:32:02,240
And you invented fish.

542
00:32:02,360 --> 00:32:03,880
Because I dislike swimming alone.

543
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:05,200
So, what's this one?

544
00:32:07,440 --> 00:32:09,880
There's a man called the Doctor.

545
00:32:10,920 --> 00:32:12,840
He lives on a cloud in the sky,

546
00:32:12,960 --> 00:32:15,280
and all he does, all day every day,

547
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:18,920
is to stop all the children in the world
ever having bad dreams.

548
00:32:19,040 --> 00:32:21,000
I've been having bad dreams.

549
00:32:21,120 --> 00:32:22,320
He's been on holiday.

550
00:32:23,880 --> 00:32:24,800
But I am confident

551
00:32:24,920 --> 00:32:26,560
he has now returned to work.

552
00:32:26,680 --> 00:32:29,040
And as a matter of fact,
he's right here.

553
00:32:29,160 --> 00:32:30,880
Aren't you, Doctor?

554
00:32:32,280 --> 00:32:33,400
(THEY SCREAM)

555
00:32:33,520 --> 00:32:34,520
Bloomin' 'ell!

556
00:32:34,640 --> 00:32:36,120
The children have been very naughty!

557
00:32:36,240 --> 00:32:38,560
Just get back, now, quickly.

558
00:32:38,680 --> 00:32:39,840
You're doing your other voice.

559
00:32:39,960 --> 00:32:41,040
Yes, love, did you notice?

560
00:32:41,160 --> 00:32:42,520
Naughty, naughty children!

561
00:32:42,640 --> 00:32:44,400
Run!

562
00:32:45,720 --> 00:32:46,960
What do we do?

563
00:32:47,080 --> 00:32:48,160
Frannie,

564
00:32:48,280 --> 00:32:49,320
Frannie,

565
00:32:49,440 --> 00:32:50,360
imagine her melting.

566
00:32:50,480 --> 00:32:51,600
- What?!
- In your 'ead! Melt her.

567
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:52,800
I can't!

568
00:32:52,920 --> 00:32:56,080
I'm getting impatient!

569
00:32:58,280 --> 00:33:01,200
You have been very naughty!

570
00:33:01,320 --> 00:33:04,080
What about the man? You said the man
was here, the cloud man.

571
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:05,720
- Well, he's not, is he?
- Where's the Doctor?

572
00:33:05,840 --> 00:33:07,840
- I don't know!
- Doctor?

573
00:33:07,960 --> 00:33:09,600
Doctor? (CHUCKLES)

574
00:33:09,720 --> 00:33:11,800
Doctor who?

575
00:33:18,880 --> 00:33:20,840
That's the way to do it!

576
00:33:23,360 --> 00:33:24,680
Oi! Ow!

577
00:33:43,040 --> 00:33:45,600
Where did she go? Will she come back?

578
00:33:45,720 --> 00:33:49,960
No, don't worry. She's currently
draining through your carpet.

579
00:33:50,080 --> 00:33:52,560
New setting, antifreeze.

580
00:33:52,680 --> 00:33:55,080
- And you're very welcome, by the way.
- I'm very grateful.

581
00:33:55,200 --> 00:33:57,480
- I knew you'd come.
- No, you didn't, because I don't.

582
00:33:57,600 --> 00:33:59,280
Because this isn't the sort of thing
I do any more.

583
00:33:59,400 --> 00:34:01,480
Next time you're in trouble,
don't expect me to...

584
00:34:05,400 --> 00:34:07,600
What is it? What's wrong?

585
00:34:07,720 --> 00:34:10,040
Sorry, it's just...

586
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:12,240
Didn't know I'd put it on.

587
00:34:20,200 --> 00:34:22,200
Old habits...

588
00:34:22,320 --> 00:34:23,800
It's cooler.

589
00:34:27,560 --> 00:34:31,200
Yeah, it is, isn't it? It is very cool.

590
00:34:32,360 --> 00:34:34,080
Bow ties are cool!

591
00:34:34,200 --> 00:34:37,200
No, the room. The room's getting colder.

592
00:34:37,320 --> 00:34:38,680
She's coming back!

593
00:34:38,800 --> 00:34:41,160
What's she going to do?
Is she going to punish me?

594
00:34:41,280 --> 00:34:43,160
Uh...uh...

595
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:44,720
She's learnt not to melt.

596
00:34:44,840 --> 00:34:48,080
Of course, she's not really a governess,
she's just a beast.

597
00:34:48,200 --> 00:34:49,600
She's going to eat you.

598
00:34:49,720 --> 00:34:51,800
Run.

599
00:34:52,040 --> 00:34:55,240
Children, what is the exp...
Who the devil are you?

600
00:34:55,360 --> 00:34:57,000
- What are you doing in my house?
- It's OK.

601
00:34:57,120 --> 00:34:59,960
I am your governess's
gentleman friend,

602
00:35:00,080 --> 00:35:01,280
and we've just been upstairs...

603
00:35:01,400 --> 00:35:02,840
kissing!

604
00:35:02,960 --> 00:35:05,440
Captain Latimer! In the garden!

605
00:35:05,560 --> 00:35:06,840
There's snowmen!

606
00:35:06,960 --> 00:35:08,360
And they're just growing,

607
00:35:08,480 --> 00:35:10,560
out of nowhere, all by themselves.

608
00:35:10,680 --> 00:35:11,680
Look!

609
00:35:12,480 --> 00:35:14,000
Good evening.

610
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:16,160
I'm a lizard woman
from the dawn of time.

611
00:35:16,280 --> 00:35:17,720
And this is my wife.

612
00:35:17,840 --> 00:35:19,840
(SCREAMS)

613
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:23,360
This dwelling is under attack.
Remain calm, human scum!

614
00:35:23,480 --> 00:35:25,080
(SCREAMS)

615
00:35:28,120 --> 00:35:29,760
So...

616
00:35:29,880 --> 00:35:31,320
any questions?

617
00:35:32,560 --> 00:35:34,360
You have a...

618
00:35:34,480 --> 00:35:37,000
- gentleman friend?
- Vastra!

619
00:35:37,120 --> 00:35:38,040
What's happening?

620
00:35:38,160 --> 00:35:40,520
The snow is highly localised
and on this occasion

621
00:35:40,640 --> 00:35:42,480
not naturally occurring.

622
00:35:42,600 --> 00:35:44,880
It's coming out of that cab
parked by the gates.

623
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:47,840
Sir, one pulver grenade
would blow these snowmen

624
00:35:47,960 --> 00:35:48,880
to smithereens!

625
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:51,440
They're made of snow, Strax,
they're already smithereens.

626
00:35:51,560 --> 00:35:54,000
See, Clara? Our friends again.

627
00:35:54,120 --> 00:35:55,200
Clara? Who is Clara?

628
00:35:55,320 --> 00:35:58,240
Your current governess is in reality
a former barmaid called Clara.

629
00:35:58,360 --> 00:36:01,560
- That's the way to do it!
- Meanwhile, your previous governess

630
00:36:01,680 --> 00:36:03,440
is now a living ice sculpture

631
00:36:03,560 --> 00:36:05,600
impersonating Mr Punch.
Jenny, what have you got?

632
00:36:09,240 --> 00:36:10,240
Should hold it.

633
00:36:10,360 --> 00:36:12,080
Sir, this room.

634
00:36:12,200 --> 00:36:14,800
One observational window on the line
of attack and one defendable entrance.

635
00:36:16,240 --> 00:36:19,240
Right, everyone in there now.
Move it. You, carry her.

636
00:36:21,280 --> 00:36:23,720
It's nice to see you off your cloud
and engaging again.

637
00:36:23,840 --> 00:36:25,560
I'm not engaging again,
I'm under attack.

638
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:27,000
You missed this, didn't you?

639
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:29,320
(GOVERNESS SHOUTS ANGRILY)

640
00:36:29,440 --> 00:36:30,440
Shut up!

641
00:36:31,800 --> 00:36:33,960
Strax, how long have we got?

642
00:36:34,080 --> 00:36:37,200
They're not going to attack. They made
no attempt to conceal their arrival.

643
00:36:37,320 --> 00:36:39,480
An attack force would never
abandon surprise so easily.

644
00:36:39,600 --> 00:36:41,480
And they're clearly
in a defence formation.

645
00:36:41,600 --> 00:36:44,520
Why-aye-aye! Well done, Straxie,

646
00:36:44,640 --> 00:36:46,640
- still got it, buddy!
- Sir, please do not

647
00:36:46,760 --> 00:36:48,960
noogie me during combat prep.

648
00:36:49,080 --> 00:36:51,680
- So there's something here they want.
- The ice woman.

649
00:36:51,800 --> 00:36:52,840
Exactly.

650
00:36:52,960 --> 00:36:55,240
- Why's she so important?
- Because she's a perfect duplication

651
00:36:55,360 --> 00:36:59,880
of human DNA in ice crystal form, the
ultimate fusion of snow and humanity.

652
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:02,880
To live here, the snow needs to evolve,
and she's the blueprint.

653
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:04,640
She's what they need to become.

654
00:37:04,760 --> 00:37:06,960
When the snow melted last night,
did the pond?

655
00:37:07,080 --> 00:37:08,600
No.

656
00:37:08,720 --> 00:37:10,640
Living ice that will never melt.

657
00:37:10,760 --> 00:37:13,000
If the snow gets hold
of that creature on the stairs,

658
00:37:13,120 --> 00:37:15,040
it will learn to make more of them.

659
00:37:15,160 --> 00:37:17,720
It will build an army of ice.

660
00:37:18,760 --> 00:37:21,680
And it will be the last day
of humanity on this planet.

661
00:37:23,400 --> 00:37:24,840
(BELL TINKLES)

662
00:37:27,280 --> 00:37:28,520
Stay here.

663
00:37:34,080 --> 00:37:35,840
Oi, I told you to stay in there.

664
00:37:35,960 --> 00:37:37,960
- Oh, I didn't listen.
- You do that a lot.

665
00:37:38,080 --> 00:37:40,360
- It's why you like me.
- Who said I like you?

666
00:37:40,480 --> 00:37:42,280
(CRY OF PAIN)

667
00:37:47,720 --> 00:37:49,080
I think you just did.

668
00:37:49,200 --> 00:37:50,440
- You kissed me.
- You blushed.

669
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:52,600
And we just...

670
00:37:52,720 --> 00:37:53,760
Shut up.

671
00:37:54,560 --> 00:37:55,880
(CRY OF PAIN)

672
00:38:06,120 --> 00:38:07,720
Release her to us.

673
00:38:07,840 --> 00:38:09,960
You have five minutes.

674
00:38:17,280 --> 00:38:19,920
We need to get her out of here
but keep her away from them.

675
00:38:20,040 --> 00:38:21,480
How?

676
00:38:21,600 --> 00:38:23,840
With this. Do I always
have to state the obvious?

677
00:38:23,960 --> 00:38:25,280
Those creatures outside, what are they?

678
00:38:25,400 --> 00:38:28,360
No danger to you, as long as I get that
thing out of here. You, in there, now.

679
00:38:31,720 --> 00:38:33,200
- What are you doing?
- Between you and me,

680
00:38:33,320 --> 00:38:34,800
I can't wait to find out.

681
00:38:36,240 --> 00:38:38,520
Right, if you look after everyone here,
then I can... Clara!

682
00:38:38,640 --> 00:38:41,240
- Doctor!
- That was stupid!

683
00:38:41,360 --> 00:38:43,400
- You were stupid, too!
- I'm allowed, I'm good at stupid!

684
00:38:43,520 --> 00:38:45,000
That's the way to do it!

685
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:47,200
- Why does she keep saying that?
- Mirroring. Random mirroring.

686
00:38:47,320 --> 00:38:48,800
- We need to get on the roof.
- This way!

687
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:51,480
No, no! I do the hand grabbing.
That's my job! That's always me!

688
00:38:51,600 --> 00:38:52,920
Come on, quickly!

689
00:38:53,040 --> 00:38:55,160
- Agh!
- What are you doing?

690
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:57,240
- My bustle is stuck.
- Your bustle?!

691
00:38:59,240 --> 00:39:01,880
You're going to have to
take those clothes off.

692
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:03,880
- I didn't mean... I just...
- I know. I understand, I do.

693
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:04,920
- Good.
- What's the plan?

694
00:39:05,040 --> 00:39:06,400
- Who said I've got a plan?
- Course you've got a plan.

695
00:39:06,520 --> 00:39:08,080
- You took that.
- Maybe I'm an idiot.

696
00:39:08,200 --> 00:39:10,120
You're not, you're clever.

697
00:39:10,240 --> 00:39:11,920
Really clever.

698
00:39:12,040 --> 00:39:12,960
Are you?

699
00:39:13,080 --> 00:39:14,720
If I've got a plan, what is it?
You tell me.

700
00:39:14,840 --> 00:39:16,360
That's the way to do it!

701
00:39:16,480 --> 00:39:17,400
- Is this a test?
- Yes.

702
00:39:17,520 --> 00:39:18,760
- What will it do to us?
- Kill us.

703
00:39:18,880 --> 00:39:20,680
That's the way to do it!

704
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:24,400
So, come on then. Plan. Do I have one?

705
00:39:24,520 --> 00:39:26,160
Oh, I know what your plan is.
I knew straightaway.

706
00:39:26,280 --> 00:39:27,640
- No, you didn't.
- Course I did.

707
00:39:27,760 --> 00:39:28,640
- Show me!
- Why should I?

708
00:39:28,760 --> 00:39:30,600
Because we'll be dead in under
30 seconds. Do I have a plan?

709
00:39:30,720 --> 00:39:33,160
If we'd been escaping,
we'd be climbing down the building.

710
00:39:33,280 --> 00:39:34,840
If we'd been hiding,
we'd be on the other side of the roof.

711
00:39:34,960 --> 00:39:37,000
But no, we're standing...

712
00:39:37,120 --> 00:39:38,040
- right here.
- So?

713
00:39:38,160 --> 00:39:39,200
So...

714
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:41,640
- After you.
- After you.

715
00:39:41,760 --> 00:39:43,720
After you, I'm wearing a dress.
Eyes front, soldier!

716
00:39:43,840 --> 00:39:44,760
My eyes are always front!

717
00:39:44,880 --> 00:39:46,840
Mine aren't.

718
00:39:49,600 --> 00:39:51,080
- Stop it.
- No!

719
00:39:52,920 --> 00:39:54,200
I understand

720
00:39:54,320 --> 00:39:58,160
you're the previous governess. I regret
to inform you the position is taken.

721
00:39:58,280 --> 00:39:59,680
Good night.

722
00:40:03,640 --> 00:40:06,600
So you can move your cloud,
you can control it?

723
00:40:06,720 --> 00:40:09,800
No. No-one can control clouds.
That would be silly.

724
00:40:09,920 --> 00:40:12,200
- The wind, a little bit.
- (METALLIC CLANGING)

725
00:40:13,640 --> 00:40:15,400
- She's following us!
- That's the idea.

726
00:40:15,520 --> 00:40:17,280
Keep her away from the snow.

727
00:40:17,400 --> 00:40:18,640
So, barmaid or governess...

728
00:40:18,760 --> 00:40:20,560
- which is it?
- That thing is after us,

729
00:40:20,680 --> 00:40:21,600
and you want a chat?

730
00:40:21,720 --> 00:40:24,520
Well, we can't chat after
we've been horribly killed, can we?

731
00:40:24,640 --> 00:40:26,600
How did we get up so high so quick?

732
00:40:26,720 --> 00:40:28,520
Clever staircase.
It's taller on the inside.

733
00:40:28,640 --> 00:40:31,120
What am I standing on?
What's this made of?

734
00:40:31,240 --> 00:40:32,480
Super-dense water vapour.

735
00:40:32,600 --> 00:40:34,880
Should keep her trapped for the moment.

736
00:40:41,720 --> 00:40:43,760
So you actually live up here?
On a cloud, in a box?

737
00:40:43,880 --> 00:40:45,000
I have done for a long time now.

738
00:40:45,120 --> 00:40:46,840
Blimey, you really know
how to sulk, don't you?

739
00:40:46,960 --> 00:40:48,280
- I'm not sulking!
- You live in a box!

740
00:40:48,400 --> 00:40:50,600
That's no more a box
than you are a governess.

741
00:40:50,720 --> 00:40:52,400
Oh, spoken like a man!

742
00:40:52,520 --> 00:40:54,000
Y'know, you're the same as all the rest.

743
00:40:54,120 --> 00:40:57,640
Sweet little Clara, works at the
Rose & Crown, ideas above her station!

744
00:40:57,760 --> 00:41:00,880
For your information, I'm not sweet
on the inside, and I'm certainly not...

745
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:08,760
...little.

746
00:41:10,240 --> 00:41:11,640
It's called the TARDIS.

747
00:41:11,760 --> 00:41:15,000
It can travel anywhere
in time and space.

748
00:41:16,760 --> 00:41:18,360
And it's mine.

749
00:41:18,480 --> 00:41:20,000
But it's...

750
00:41:22,240 --> 00:41:23,440
Look at it, it's...

751
00:41:23,560 --> 00:41:26,400
Go on, say it. Most people do.

752
00:41:37,880 --> 00:41:39,400
It's smaller on the outside.

753
00:41:41,320 --> 00:41:44,040
OK. That is a first.

754
00:41:44,160 --> 00:41:46,280
Is it magic? Is it a machine?

755
00:41:46,400 --> 00:41:48,240
- It's a ship.
- (CHUCKLES) A ship?

756
00:41:48,360 --> 00:41:49,840
Best ship in the universe.

757
00:41:53,960 --> 00:41:55,680
Is there a kitchen?

758
00:41:55,800 --> 00:41:56,880
Another first.

759
00:41:57,000 --> 00:41:58,760
I don't know why I asked that,
it's just...

760
00:41:58,880 --> 00:42:00,480
I like making souffles.

761
00:42:04,960 --> 00:42:06,280
Souffles?!

762
00:42:07,880 --> 00:42:09,800
Why are you showing me all this?

763
00:42:09,920 --> 00:42:12,240
You followed me. Remember?

764
00:42:12,360 --> 00:42:14,920
- I didn't invite you.
- You're nearly a foot taller than I am.

765
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:21,480
You could've reached the ladder
without this.

766
00:42:21,600 --> 00:42:24,080
You took it for me.

767
00:42:24,200 --> 00:42:25,640
Why?

768
00:42:33,080 --> 00:42:35,240
I never know why.

769
00:42:35,360 --> 00:42:37,680
I only know who.

770
00:42:48,040 --> 00:42:48,960
What's this?

771
00:42:49,080 --> 00:42:50,640
Me.

772
00:42:51,680 --> 00:42:53,080
Giving in.

773
00:43:00,200 --> 00:43:02,280
- I don't know why I'm crying.
- I do.

774
00:43:02,400 --> 00:43:06,080
Remember this.
Remember this right now, all of it,

775
00:43:06,200 --> 00:43:08,320
because this is the day,

776
00:43:08,440 --> 00:43:09,640
this is the day,

777
00:43:09,760 --> 00:43:13,320
this is the day everything begins!

778
00:43:18,280 --> 00:43:20,040
Clara!

779
00:43:20,160 --> 00:43:22,360
- Clara!
- Get off of me!

780
00:43:22,480 --> 00:43:24,880
Water vapour doesn't stop ice.
I should've realised!

781
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:26,680
- Get off!
- Let her go. Let her go now!

782
00:43:26,800 --> 00:43:28,120
- Now!
- Get off of me!

783
00:43:28,240 --> 00:43:30,240
No!

784
00:43:30,360 --> 00:43:32,560
Clara!

785
00:43:38,240 --> 00:43:41,200
Clara!

786
00:43:42,840 --> 00:43:43,760
(THUD)

787
00:43:43,880 --> 00:43:45,040
What was that?

788
00:43:45,160 --> 00:43:46,920
It's Clara.

789
00:43:47,040 --> 00:43:49,720
- (BLEEPING)
- Dear God.

790
00:43:49,840 --> 00:43:51,440
Oh, dear God.

791
00:43:51,560 --> 00:43:53,640
Where did she fall from?

792
00:43:55,480 --> 00:43:56,840
We have to get her inside.

793
00:43:57,880 --> 00:43:59,480
- Those things will kill you.
- She's hurt.

794
00:43:59,600 --> 00:44:00,880
She's dead.

795
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:06,800
- (METALLIC THRUMMING)
- What is that?

796
00:44:06,920 --> 00:44:08,360
What is happening?!

797
00:44:22,160 --> 00:44:23,560
He's bringing her in.

798
00:44:40,120 --> 00:44:42,320
That...green woman said she was dead.

799
00:44:42,440 --> 00:44:44,320
- How can she be alive now?
- This technology

800
00:44:44,440 --> 00:44:46,760
has capacities and abilities
beyond anything

801
00:44:46,880 --> 00:44:48,960
your puny human mind
could possibly understand.

802
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:52,000
Try not to worry.

803
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:11,120
Isn't the creature still a danger?
It could re-form.

804
00:45:11,240 --> 00:45:13,320
No, not in here.

805
00:45:13,440 --> 00:45:15,200
Then you should be with Miss Clara.

806
00:45:15,320 --> 00:45:17,840
She's going to be fine. I know she is.

807
00:45:17,960 --> 00:45:19,480
She has to be.

808
00:45:19,600 --> 00:45:22,160
Doctor, her injuries are severe.

809
00:45:22,280 --> 00:45:25,000
That equipment will bring back
anyone for a while, but long term...

810
00:45:25,120 --> 00:45:29,680
It was my fault. I am responsible
for what happened to Clara.

811
00:45:31,360 --> 00:45:33,040
What is the point of blaming yourself?

812
00:45:34,280 --> 00:45:35,520
None.

813
00:45:38,520 --> 00:45:40,320
Because she's going to live.

814
00:46:00,080 --> 00:46:01,080
Hm...

815
00:46:02,360 --> 00:46:03,400
Hey.

816
00:46:03,520 --> 00:46:05,680
Hello.

817
00:46:05,800 --> 00:46:08,680
They all think I'm going to die,
don't they?

818
00:46:08,800 --> 00:46:11,400
And I know you're going to live.

819
00:46:12,720 --> 00:46:14,040
How?

820
00:46:14,160 --> 00:46:15,880
I never know how.

821
00:46:19,200 --> 00:46:22,040
I just know...who.

822
00:46:27,520 --> 00:46:29,280
The green lady...

823
00:46:31,200 --> 00:46:33,840
...she said you were
the saver of worlds once.

824
00:46:36,640 --> 00:46:38,080
Are you going to save this one?

825
00:46:39,800 --> 00:46:41,400
If I do...

826
00:46:42,560 --> 00:46:45,160
...will you come away with me?

827
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:51,000
Yes.

828
00:46:54,280 --> 00:46:56,400
Well, then...

829
00:47:00,680 --> 00:47:02,560
...merry Christmas.

830
00:47:29,840 --> 00:47:31,960
I have in my hand

831
00:47:32,080 --> 00:47:34,120
a piece of the ice lady...

832
00:47:35,520 --> 00:47:36,880
...everything you need to know

833
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:39,160
about how to make ice people.

834
00:47:40,760 --> 00:47:42,360
Is that what you want?

835
00:47:44,240 --> 00:47:46,120
See you at the office.

836
00:47:50,280 --> 00:47:53,880
So, then, Doctor,
saving the world again? Might I ask why?

837
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:56,000
Are you making a bargain
with the universe?

838
00:47:56,120 --> 00:47:57,520
You'll save the world to let her live?

839
00:47:57,640 --> 00:47:59,800
Yes! And don't you think,
after all this time

840
00:47:59,920 --> 00:48:02,480
and everything I have ever done,
that I am owed this one?

841
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:04,320
I don't think the universe
makes bargains.

842
00:48:04,440 --> 00:48:06,720
- It was my fault.
- Well, then...

843
00:48:07,880 --> 00:48:09,320
...better save the world.

844
00:48:26,120 --> 00:48:27,480
You promised us something.

845
00:48:27,600 --> 00:48:29,000
Have you brought it?

846
00:48:29,120 --> 00:48:32,360
Big fella here's been very quiet
while you've been out,

847
00:48:32,480 --> 00:48:33,800
which is only to be expected,

848
00:48:33,920 --> 00:48:36,360
considering who he really is.

849
00:48:38,520 --> 00:48:40,080
You know what this is, big fella?

850
00:48:40,200 --> 00:48:41,800
I do not understand these markings.

851
00:48:41,920 --> 00:48:47,040
A map of the London Underground, 1967.

852
00:48:47,160 --> 00:48:50,640
Key strategic weakness
in metropolitan living, if you ask me,

853
00:48:50,760 --> 00:48:53,440
but then, I have never liked a tunnel.

854
00:48:53,560 --> 00:48:54,920
Enough of this.

855
00:48:55,040 --> 00:48:56,440
We are powerful, but on this planet,

856
00:48:56,560 --> 00:48:58,520
we are limited.

857
00:48:58,640 --> 00:49:01,240
We need to learn to take human form.

858
00:49:01,360 --> 00:49:03,600
The governess is our most
perfect replication... (VOICE DISTORTS)

859
00:49:03,720 --> 00:49:07,120
- CHILD'S VOICE: ...of humanity...
- What's happening to its voice?

860
00:49:07,240 --> 00:49:08,800
Just stripping away the disguise.

861
00:49:08,920 --> 00:49:10,160
No! Stop!

862
00:49:10,280 --> 00:49:11,160
Stop that.

863
00:49:11,280 --> 00:49:13,240
Cease, I command you!

864
00:49:13,360 --> 00:49:14,600
It sounds like a child.

865
00:49:14,720 --> 00:49:16,280
Of course it sounds like a child,
it ls a child.

866
00:49:16,400 --> 00:49:18,720
Simeon as a child.
The snow has no voice without him.

867
00:49:18,840 --> 00:49:20,800
Don't listen to him.
He's ruining everything!

868
00:49:20,920 --> 00:49:23,400
How long has the Intelligence
been talking to you?

869
00:49:24,800 --> 00:49:26,120
I was a little boy.

870
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:28,000
He was my snowman.

871
00:49:29,760 --> 00:49:30,960
He spoke to me.

872
00:49:31,080 --> 00:49:32,400
They're silly.

873
00:49:33,480 --> 00:49:36,640
Snow doesn't talk, does it?
It's just a mirror.

874
00:49:36,760 --> 00:49:39,200
I don't want to talk to them.
They're silly.

875
00:49:39,320 --> 00:49:40,760
They're silly.

876
00:49:40,880 --> 00:49:44,320
It just reflects back everything
we think and feel and fear.

877
00:49:44,440 --> 00:49:47,400
I don't need anyone else.

878
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:49,800
Don't need anyone else.

879
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:51,920
You poured your darkest dreams

880
00:49:52,040 --> 00:49:53,360
into a snowman. And look!

881
00:49:53,480 --> 00:49:54,800
Look what it became!

882
00:49:54,920 --> 00:49:56,280
I don't understand.

883
00:49:57,680 --> 00:49:59,800
It's a parasite
feeding on the loneliness of a child

884
00:49:59,920 --> 00:50:02,000
and the sickness of an old man.

885
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:06,520
Carnivorous snow...

886
00:50:06,640 --> 00:50:08,680
meets Victorian values...

887
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:11,800
...and something terrible is born.

888
00:50:12,960 --> 00:50:15,200
We can go on
and do everything we planned.

889
00:50:15,320 --> 00:50:19,160
Oh, yes, and what a plan.
A world full of living ice people.

890
00:50:20,720 --> 00:50:22,720
Oh, dear me...

891
00:50:22,840 --> 00:50:24,760
how very Victorian of you.

892
00:50:24,880 --> 00:50:27,520
What's wrong with Victorian values?

893
00:50:29,080 --> 00:50:30,320
Ah-ah-ah. Are you sure?

894
00:50:31,680 --> 00:50:33,480
I have always been sure.

895
00:50:36,640 --> 00:50:37,800
Good.

896
00:50:40,840 --> 00:50:43,440
I'm glad you think so...

897
00:50:44,600 --> 00:50:47,360
...since your entire adult life
is about to be erased.

898
00:50:47,480 --> 00:50:51,680
No parasite without a host.
Without you, it will have no voice.

899
00:50:51,800 --> 00:50:53,320
Without the governess,

900
00:50:53,440 --> 00:50:55,200
it will have no form.

901
00:50:57,120 --> 00:50:58,200
What...

902
00:50:58,320 --> 00:50:59,760
What... What's happening?

903
00:50:59,880 --> 00:51:01,960
What's happening? What did you do?

904
00:51:03,040 --> 00:51:06,040
You've got nothing left
to mirror any more.

905
00:51:07,320 --> 00:51:08,320
Goodbye.

906
00:51:08,440 --> 00:51:10,480
What did you... Did you...

907
00:51:10,600 --> 00:51:12,880
(VOICE DISTORTS) Did you...

908
00:51:14,240 --> 00:51:17,240
MAN'S VOICE: Did you really think
it would be so easy?

909
00:51:17,360 --> 00:51:19,400
That's not possible.

910
00:51:20,960 --> 00:51:22,680
How is that possible?

911
00:51:22,800 --> 00:51:24,440
Doctor!

912
00:51:36,760 --> 00:51:38,960
(SNOWMEN ROAR)

913
00:51:41,040 --> 00:51:44,320
They're growing!
The snowmen are growing!

914
00:51:46,040 --> 00:51:47,280
What do we do?

915
00:51:47,400 --> 00:51:49,440
But you were just Dr Simeon.
You're not real.

916
00:51:49,560 --> 00:51:52,560
He dreamed you.

917
00:51:52,680 --> 00:51:55,040
How can you still exist?

918
00:51:55,160 --> 00:51:58,560
Now the dream outlives the dreamer
and can never die.

919
00:51:58,680 --> 00:52:01,160
Once I was the puppet...

920
00:52:01,280 --> 00:52:02,880
...now I pull the strings!

921
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:05,200
I tried...

922
00:52:05,320 --> 00:52:09,160
so long to take on human form.

923
00:52:09,280 --> 00:52:12,360
By erasing Simeon,

924
00:52:12,480 --> 00:52:14,480
you made space for me.

925
00:52:16,120 --> 00:52:17,800
I fill him now.

926
00:52:21,080 --> 00:52:24,560
More than snow, more than Simeon.

927
00:52:24,680 --> 00:52:26,480
Even this old body...

928
00:52:26,600 --> 00:52:29,440
is strong in my control.

929
00:52:32,560 --> 00:52:34,040
Do you feel it?

930
00:52:36,320 --> 00:52:38,520
Winter is coming!

931
00:52:38,640 --> 00:52:43,120
- (CRIES OUT)
- Winter is coming!

932
00:52:44,160 --> 00:52:47,640
No, you must fight!
Hang on and fight, boy. You can do it!

933
00:52:47,760 --> 00:52:48,880
Captain Latimer...

934
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:50,560
Mm?

935
00:52:50,680 --> 00:52:51,920
...your children...

936
00:52:54,080 --> 00:52:55,400
...they're afraid.

937
00:52:57,280 --> 00:52:58,720
Hold them.

938
00:52:58,840 --> 00:53:02,120
It's not...really my area.

939
00:53:02,240 --> 00:53:04,600
It is now.

940
00:53:10,480 --> 00:53:12,560
(THUNDER CRASHES)

941
00:53:14,200 --> 00:53:16,720
(SCREAMING)

942
00:53:22,640 --> 00:53:24,400
What's happening?

943
00:53:27,040 --> 00:53:27,960
Doctor!

944
00:53:28,080 --> 00:53:31,120
The globe. It's turning to rain.

945
00:53:31,240 --> 00:53:32,640
All of it. The snow. Look.

946
00:53:45,560 --> 00:53:46,560
He's dead.

947
00:53:47,800 --> 00:53:49,040
What happened?

948
00:53:49,160 --> 00:53:50,880
The snow mirrors. That's all it does.

949
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:53,000
It's mirroring something else now,

950
00:53:53,120 --> 00:53:55,960
something so strong
it's drowning everything else.

951
00:53:56,080 --> 00:53:58,120
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

952
00:54:08,880 --> 00:54:12,840
There was a critical mass of snow at the
house. If something happened there...

953
00:54:18,240 --> 00:54:21,080
Salty. Saltwater rain.

954
00:54:21,200 --> 00:54:23,080
It's not raining.

955
00:54:23,200 --> 00:54:24,600
It's crying.

956
00:54:25,640 --> 00:54:27,960
The only force on earth
that could drown the snow,

957
00:54:28,080 --> 00:54:30,320
a whole family crying on Christmas Eve.

958
00:54:35,160 --> 00:54:37,560
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

959
00:54:44,400 --> 00:54:46,520
(SOBBING)

960
00:54:46,640 --> 00:54:47,560
I'm sorry.

961
00:54:47,680 --> 00:54:50,080
There was nothing to be done.

962
00:54:50,200 --> 00:54:52,680
She has moments only.

963
00:55:12,520 --> 00:55:13,960
We saved the world, Clara,

964
00:55:14,080 --> 00:55:15,440
you and me.

965
00:55:16,560 --> 00:55:18,280
We really, really did.

966
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:21,400
Will you go back...

967
00:55:21,520 --> 00:55:23,600
to your cloud?

968
00:55:23,720 --> 00:55:25,520
No more cloud. Not now.

969
00:55:27,560 --> 00:55:29,400
Why not?

970
00:55:36,160 --> 00:55:37,520
It rained.

971
00:55:45,040 --> 00:55:46,960
Run.

972
00:55:47,080 --> 00:55:50,080
Run, you clever boy.

973
00:55:54,440 --> 00:55:56,000
And remember.

974
00:55:56,120 --> 00:55:59,360
(CLOCK CHIMES)

975
00:55:59,480 --> 00:56:00,480
JENNY: It's Christmas.

976
00:56:03,160 --> 00:56:04,400
Christmas Day.

977
00:56:16,280 --> 00:56:19,920
VASTRA: And what about the Intelligence?
Melted with the snow?

978
00:56:20,040 --> 00:56:21,360
THE DOCTOR: No, I shouldn't think so.

979
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:24,600
It learned to survive
beyond physical form.

980
00:56:24,720 --> 00:56:27,640
Well, we can't be in much danger
from a disembodied Intelligence

981
00:56:27,760 --> 00:56:29,920
that thinks it can invade the world
with snowmen.

982
00:56:30,040 --> 00:56:33,760
Or that the London Underground
is a key strategic weakness.

983
00:56:39,040 --> 00:56:41,880
The Great Intelligence... Rings a bell.

984
00:56:44,560 --> 00:56:46,360
The Great Intelligence...

985
00:56:46,480 --> 00:56:48,520
Doctor?

986
00:57:00,240 --> 00:57:01,160
I never knew her name,

987
00:57:01,280 --> 00:57:02,880
her full name.

988
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:05,680
Oswin Oswald, junior entertainment
manager, Starship Alaska.

989
00:57:05,800 --> 00:57:07,960
Souffle girl.

990
00:57:08,080 --> 00:57:09,480
(TIMER PINGS)

991
00:57:09,600 --> 00:57:11,000
Oswin.

992
00:57:12,040 --> 00:57:13,400
It was her.

993
00:57:13,520 --> 00:57:15,400
Run, you clever boy.

994
00:57:15,520 --> 00:57:17,760
Run, you clever boy.

995
00:57:17,880 --> 00:57:19,640
And remember.

996
00:57:19,760 --> 00:57:21,200
And remember.

997
00:57:21,320 --> 00:57:23,920
It was souffle girl again!

998
00:57:25,040 --> 00:57:28,520
I never saw her face the first time
with the Daleks, but her voice,

999
00:57:28,640 --> 00:57:30,400
it was the same voice.

1000
00:57:30,520 --> 00:57:31,840
- Doctor?
- The same woman,

1001
00:57:31,960 --> 00:57:35,560
twice, and she died both times,
the same woman!

1002
00:57:35,680 --> 00:57:37,480
Doctor, please,
what are you talking about?

1003
00:57:37,600 --> 00:57:40,080
Something's going on,
something impossible, something...

1004
00:57:41,640 --> 00:57:44,960
Right, you two stay here.
Stay right here. Don't move an inch.

1005
00:57:45,080 --> 00:57:46,760
- Are you coming back?
- Shouldn't think so!

1006
00:57:46,880 --> 00:57:47,960
But where are you going?

1007
00:57:49,040 --> 00:57:51,320
To find her. To find Clara.

1008
00:57:51,440 --> 00:57:53,000
(HE LAUGHS)

1009
00:57:53,120 --> 00:57:56,200
But Clara's dead.
What's he talking about,

1010
00:57:56,320 --> 00:57:58,600
- finding her?
- I don't know!

1011
00:57:58,720 --> 00:58:02,920
But perhaps the universe
makes bargains after all.

1012
00:58:06,600 --> 00:58:08,600
Where are you going?

1013
00:58:08,720 --> 00:58:10,320
- Short cut.
- Through there?

1014
00:58:10,440 --> 00:58:12,840
I hate this place!
Don't you think it's creepy?

1015
00:58:14,160 --> 00:58:15,360
No.

1016
00:58:16,400 --> 00:58:17,720
I don't believe in ghosts.

1017
00:58:21,240 --> 00:58:22,920
Clara!

1018
00:58:23,040 --> 00:58:24,760
Oswin!

1019
00:58:24,880 --> 00:58:26,600
Oswald!

1020
00:58:26,720 --> 00:58:28,040
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

1021
00:58:29,520 --> 00:58:30,520
Watch me run!

1022
00:59:00,080 --> 00:59:01,840
Ha-ha! Miss me?

1023
00:59:01,960 --> 00:59:03,160
Who the hell are you?

1024
00:59:03,280 --> 00:59:05,320
I'm the Doctor.
I'm an alien from outer space.

1025
00:59:05,440 --> 00:59:08,880
I'm 1,000 years old. I've got
two hearts. And I can't fly a plane!

1026
00:59:09,000 --> 00:59:11,520
You're running away with a spaceman
in a box. Anything could happen to you.

1027
00:59:12,600 --> 00:59:14,200
That's what I'm counting on.

1028
00:59:14,320 --> 00:59:17,240
Where do you want to go, hey?
What do you want to see?

1029
00:59:26,480 --> 00:59:27,880
Is that her?

1030
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:29,600
The woman twice dead.

1031
00:59:29,720 --> 00:59:31,000
She's rather pretty, isn't she?

1032
00:59:31,120 --> 00:59:32,720
She's not possible.

1033
00:59:34,720 --> 00:59:36,200
Right, then, Clara Oswald...

1034
00:59:38,720 --> 00:59:40,960
...time to find out who you are.

